<div class="indented"><a id="comment-124355"></a>
<div class="comment comment-published odd comment-by-anon"><div class="comment-inner clear-block">

      <h3 class="title">
      <a href="/article/7684#comment-124355" class="active">Spinrite which make your back</a>          </h3>
  
  
  <div class="picture">
  <img src="/files/linuxjournal.com/images/personicon.jpg" alt="Anonymous&#039;s picture" title="Anonymous&#039;s picture"  /></div>

  <div class="submitted">
    Submitted by Anonymous (not verified) on Sat, 08/20/2005 - 04:25.  </div>

  <div class="content">
    <p>Spinrite which make your back up a redundancy of a redundancy and although you may continue to make backups etc, using Sprinrite level 5 pretty much makes it so you'll never make use of those backups -- since the drive will be "repaired" by Spinrite BEFORE failure. That is to say, the failure won't happen and you won't need your backup. Whether you make backups or not. </p>
<p>There are still moving parts within the harddrive that can fail at any time, heads can crash on the platters, components can fry, which even Sprinrite cannot fix. So to be safe backups are a must!</p>
      </div>

  
